Day 5 code
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
#progressBar {
position: fixed;
top: 0;
left: 0;
height: 5px;
width: 0%;
background: linear-gradient(to right, #ff6b6b, #4ecdc4);
z-index: 999;
}
.content {
height: 3000px;
padding-top: 30px;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div id="progressBar"></div>
<div class="content"><h1>check progress bar</h1></div> <script>
const bar = document.getElementById("progressBar");
window.addEventListener("scroll", () => {
const scrolled = window.scrollY;
const total =
document.documentElement.scrollHeight - window.innerHeight;
const percent = (scrolled / total) * 100;
bar.style.width = percent + "%";
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
This code makes a thin bar appear at the top of the page. At first, the bar has no width. As you scroll down, the code checks how far you have moved through the page and makes the bar wider. When you are near the top, the bar is short. When you are near the bottom, the bar stretches almost all the way across the screen. Visually, it works like a reading progress indicator.
1/ HTML Structure
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
/* CSS */
</style>
</head>
<body>
/* DOM element */
<script>
/* JavaScript */
</script>
</body>
</html>The CSS is embedded directly in the <head>HTML file. The JavaScript appears within <body> .
2/ CSS elements
<style>
#progressBar {
position: fixed;
top: 0;
left: 0;
height: 5px;
width: 0%;
background: linear-gradient(to right, #ff6b6b, #4ecdc4);
z-index: 999;
}
.content {
height: 3000px;
padding-top: 30px;
}
</style>First, the CSS rule #progressBar selects the HTML element with id="progressBar" and gives it the styling for the progress bar. It fixes the bar to the top-left corner of the browser window, makes it 5px tall, starts its width at 0%, gives it a left-to-right gradient color, and places it above most other page content using z-index: 999. Then, the .content rule selects any element with class="content" and gives it a large height of 3000px, which makes the page scrollable. It also adds 30px of space at the top so the content does not start directly under the progress bar.
3/ JS method with DOM
// DOM
<div id="progressBar"></div>
<div class="content"><h1>check progress bar</h1></div><script>
const bar = document.getElementById("progressBar");
window.addEventListener("scroll", () => {
const scrolled = window.scrollY;
const total =
document.documentElement.scrollHeight - window.innerHeight;
const percent = (scrolled / total) * 100;
bar.style.width = percent + "%";
});
</script>
First, the HTML creates two elements in the page’s DOM: one empty <div> with id="progressBar", which will become the visual progress bar later, and another <div> with class="content", which contains the heading text. In JavaScript, document.getElementById("progressBar") selects the element with that ID and stores a reference to it in the variable bar. Then, window.addEventListener("scroll", ...) registers a callback that runs whenever the user scrolls the page. Inside that function, the code gets how far the user has scrolled, calculates the total scrollable distance, converts the current scroll position into a percentage, and updates the progress bar’s width viabar.style.width. So as the user scrolls down, the progress bar becomes wider.
